# tf-az-backend — Per-environment Terraform remote state on Azure

This folder is the **scaffolding for environment-isolated remote state**. It does not deploy any workloads. Instead, each `env/<environment>/` folder is a Terraform root config that's wired up to store its state in a dedicated container inside the shared Azure Storage Account `terraformtatesa`. Drop workload `.tf` files into one of these folders and the state for that environment lives in its own container, separate from the others.

---

## What lives where

```
tf-az-backend/
└── env/
    ├── dev/
    │   ├── backend.tf      # azurerm backend → terraformtatesa / tf-az-dev
    │   └── providers.tf
    ├── stg/
    │   ├── backend.tf      # azurerm backend → terraformtatesa / tf-az-stg
    │   └── providers.tf
    └── prd/
        ├── backend.tf      # azurerm backend → terraformtatesa / tf-az-prd
        └── providers.tf
```

Each env folder contains exactly two files today; both are intentionally minimal so future workload code (`main.tf`, `variables.tf`, etc.) can be added next to them without conflict.

---

## What's hand-managed (outside Terraform)

The backend infrastructure itself is **not** managed by this folder. It was created by hand once and lives outside Terraform's blast radius — that's the whole point of this layout.

| Resource | Where | Purpose |
|----------|-------|---------|
| Resource group `aztools` | Azure | Holds the storage account. |
| Storage account `terraformtatesa` | `aztools` | Single shared SA for all env state files. |
| Container `tf-az-dev` | `terraformtatesa` | Holds `terraform.tfstate` for the dev environment. |
| Container `tf-az-stg` | `terraformtatesa` | Holds `terraform.tfstate` for the stg environment. |
| Container `tf-az-prd` | `terraformtatesa` | Holds `terraform.tfstate` for the prd environment. |

**Why hand-managed?** If Terraform also created the containers it stores its own state in, two things break: (1) the very first `terraform init` fails because the backend points at a container that doesn't exist yet, forcing a comment-out → apply → uncomment → `init -migrate-state` dance per environment, and (2) `terraform destroy` from inside an env folder tries to delete the container holding its own state mid-operation. Splitting "platform infra" (the SA + containers) from "app infra" (anything you add to an env folder) avoids both problems.

If you ever need to recreate the containers from scratch:

```bash
az storage container create --name tf-az-dev --account-name terraformtatesa --auth-mode login
az storage container create --name tf-az-stg --account-name terraformtatesa --auth-mode login
az storage container create --name tf-az-prd --account-name terraformtatesa --auth-mode login
```

---

## How the backend is configured

Every env folder has a `backend.tf` with the same shape; only the `container_name` line changes between them. Here's `env/dev/backend.tf`:

```hcl
terraform {
  backend "azurerm" {
    resource_group_name  = "aztools"
    storage_account_name = "terraformtatesa"
    container_name       = "tf-az-dev"
    key                  = "terraform.tfstate"
  }
}
```

| Field | Value | Notes |
|-------|-------|-------|
| `resource_group_name` | `aztools` | RG that contains the SA. |
| `storage_account_name` | `terraformtatesa` | Globally unique. Hand-created. |
| `container_name` | `tf-az-{env}` | **The only thing that differs per env.** Provides state isolation. |
| `key` | `terraform.tfstate` | Blob name within the container. Same value across envs because each env has its own container. |

`stg/backend.tf` and `prd/backend.tf` are identical except `container_name` is `tf-az-stg` and `tf-az-prd` respectively.

The Terraform documentation for this block is at [hashicorp/terraform — Azure backend](https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/backend/azurerm). Backend blocks **cannot** use variables — that's why the values are hardcoded literally and why each env has its own `backend.tf`.

---

## Authenticating

Backend blocks don't carry credentials; Terraform picks them up from the environment. Two common paths:

**Azure CLI identity (recommended for local dev):**
```bash
az login
export ARM_SUBSCRIPTION_ID=<your-sub-id>
```
The identity logged in needs **Storage Blob Data Contributor** on `terraformtatesa` so it can read/write state blobs. Reader on the SA is not enough.

**Storage account access key (fallback):**
```bash
export ARM_ACCESS_KEY="$(az storage account keys list \
  --account-name terraformtatesa \
  --query '[0].value' -o tsv)"
```
This works without the data-plane RBAC but exposes a long-lived shared key — fine for sandbox, avoid for prod.

---

## How to use it

### Initialize an environment

```bash
cd env/dev          # or stg, or prd
terraform init      # contacts terraformtatesa/tf-az-dev, sets up the backend
```

The first `init` writes a small `.terraform/terraform.tfstate` lockfile reference locally and creates an empty `terraform.tfstate` blob in the container if one doesn't exist.

### Plan / apply (with no resources yet)

```bash
terraform plan      # "No changes. Your infrastructure matches the configuration."
```

This is expected — `env/<env>/` only has the backend wiring, no resources. As soon as you add `main.tf` (or any other `.tf` files defining resources) next to `backend.tf` and `providers.tf`, `terraform plan` and `apply` will work normally and the resulting state will land in the right container.

### Adding a workload to an environment

Example — to host the `tf-vm-maps` Linux VM stack with its `dev` state stored remotely:

```bash
cp ../../tf-vm-maps/main.tf      env/dev/
cp ../../tf-vm-maps/variables.tf env/dev/
cp ../../tf-vm-maps/locals.tf    env/dev/
cp ../../tf-vm-maps/keypair.tf   env/dev/
cp ../../tf-vm-maps/outputs.tf   env/dev/
cd env/dev
terraform init                   # picks up the new resources, backend already configured
terraform apply -var environment=dev
```

After apply, `terraform.tfstate` lives in `terraformtatesa/tf-az-dev/terraform.tfstate`.

---

## Switching between environments

There is no implicit "current environment" — `cd` into the folder you want to operate on. Each folder is independent:

```bash
cd env/dev && terraform plan     # touches only tf-az-dev
cd ../stg  && terraform plan     # touches only tf-az-stg
cd ../prd  && terraform plan     # touches only tf-az-prd
```

This is the deliberate alternative to Terraform workspaces: explicit folders make it obvious which environment you're acting on, and there's no `terraform workspace select` step to forget.

---

## What this layout gives you

- **State isolation per environment.** A bad `apply` in dev cannot corrupt stg or prd state.
- **Always-active backends.** No first-run comment-out dance.
- **Safe `terraform destroy`.** State is in a container Terraform doesn't manage, so destroy never operates on its own footing.
- **Clean blast-radius separation.** Permissions on `terraformtatesa` are managed once at the SA level, independent of any env's Terraform code.

---

## Deviations from production guidance

- **Single shared storage account across all envs.** Production typically isolates state per env in its own SA (or at least per-env access policies) so a compromised dev credential can't read prod state. Here all three containers live in one SA — fine for sandbox; consider splitting if you go past that.
- **No state locking is configured by name.** The azurerm backend uses **blob leases** for locking automatically, so concurrent `apply`s are safe — but be aware there's no separate Cosmos DB / DynamoDB-style lock table; the lock lives on the state blob itself.
- **No state versioning enabled by default.** Verify in the portal that the SA has **Blob versioning** + **Soft delete (7+ days)** turned on — otherwise an accidental `terraform state rm` followed by an apply can lose history. Storage account → Data protection.
- **Long-lived storage account keys** are still enabled on the SA. Prefer Entra ID auth (`--auth-mode login` on `az` commands, AAD-based RBAC for Terraform) and disable shared keys via `allow_shared_key_access = false` on the SA when ready.
